      },
      {
        "from": "PaymentService",
        "to": "StripeAPI",
        "status": "risk",
        "issue": "Circuit breaker exists (5-failure, 60s reset) but 10s timeout is aggressive for thread pool starvation during gray failures. 8s latency within timeout means requests succeed slowly but circuit never opens, collapsing throughput silently."
      },
      {
        "from": "PaymentService",
        "to": "PostgreSQL",
        "status": "risk",
        "issue": "Connection pool of 10 with 20 worker threads is a 2:1 mismatch. No connection retry means transient DB hiccups cause immediate hard failures. Pool exhaustion cascades to full service unavailability."
      }
    ],
    "contract_compliance": "Service has no documented SLAs for degraded-mode behavior. No fallback contracts defined for fraud detection bypass or payment queueing during outages.",
    "data_flow_integrity": "Payment flow is synchronous and serial: fraud check → Stripe charge → DB write. Any single link failure blocks the entire chain with no async fallback or eventual-consistency path."
  },

  "observability_review": {
    "logging": {
      "coverage": "gaps",
      "gaps": [
        "No mention of structured error logging with correlation IDs for tracing a payment through fraud → Stripe → DB",
        "No logging of circuit breaker state transitions (open/half-open/closed)",
        "No logging of connection pool utilization or wait times",
        "No logging of thread pool saturation or request queuing"
      ]
    },
    "metrics": {
      "coverage": "Three metrics exist (payments_total, stripe_api_duration_histogram, fraud_check_duration_histogram) but critical operational metrics are missing",
      "gaps": [
        "No DB connection pool utilization metric (active/idle/waiting connections)",
        "No worker thread pool utilization metric (active/total/queued)",
        "No circuit breaker state metric (open/closed/half-open)",
        "No error rate metric broken down by dependency (fraud vs stripe vs db)",
        "No request queue depth or rejection count metric",
        "No fraud_check_error_total or stripe_api_error_total counters",
        "No payment latency end-to-end histogram (only individual dependency durations)"
      ]
    },
    "tracing": {
      "coverage": "No distributed tracing mentioned. Cannot trace a payment request across fraud detection → Stripe → DB write.",
      "gaps": [
        "No span-level tracing for individual dependency calls within a payment request",
        "No trace context propagation to fraud detection service"
      ]
    },
    "debugging_capability": "Poor. At 3am, an on-call engineer would see payments_total drop but could not distinguish between fraud service failure, Stripe failure, DB failure, or thread exhaustion from existing metrics alone. No circuit breaker visibility. No connection pool visibility."
  },

  "resilience_assessment": {
    "failure_modes": [
      {
        "scenario": "A: Fraud detection service returns 503 for 5 minutes",
        "handling": "unhandled",
        "recommendation": "PREDICTION: Every payment request still calls fraud detection, waits up to 2s, gets 503, then fails. No circuit breaker means all 20 threads cycle through 2s timeouts continuously — throughput drops to ~10 failing req/s instead of failing fast. 100% payment failure for 5 minutes. SURVIVABILITY: Service survives (threads recycle) but ALL payments fail. FIX: Add circuit breaker (e.g., 3 failures in 10s → open for 30s). Consider a risk-based fallback: allow low-value payments to proceed without fraud check during outage, or queue for async fraud review."
      },
      {
        "scenario": "B: Database connection pool exhaustion for 30 seconds",
        "handling": "unhandled",
        "recommendation": "PREDICTION: 10 DB connections exhausted, no retry. Worker threads that complete fraud+Stripe successfully then fail at DB write — payment charged but not recorded (data loss risk). Remaining threads queue for DB connections. If connection acquire has no timeout, all 20 threads block waiting for DB, causing full service freeze. Health checks may fail. Load balancer may pull the instance. SURVIVABILITY: Likely cascading failure. Payments may be charged at Stripe but never recorded locally. FIX: Add connection acquire timeout (500ms), add connection retry with backoff, increase pool to match thread count (20), implement write-ahead to a local queue or WAL so charged payments are never lost."
      },
      {
        "scenario": "C: Stripe API latency increases to 8s for 10 minutes",
        "handling": "unhandled",
        "recommendation": "PREDICTION: Classic gray failure. 8s < 10s timeout so all Stripe calls succeed — circuit breaker never trips. But each request now occupies a worker thread for ~10s (2s fraud + 8s Stripe). With 20 threads, max throughput drops to ~2 req/s. Under any normal load, thread pool saturates within seconds. New requests queue up, timeouts cascade, and the service appears hung despite every individual call 'succeeding.' SURVIVABILITY: Service stays up but effective capacity collapses by 80-90%. This is the most dangerous scenario because nothing alerts — no errors, no circuit breaker, just slow success. FIX: Add an adaptive timeout or latency-based circuit breaker (trip at p99 > 5s). Add thread pool utilization metric with alert at 80%. Consider request shedding when queue depth exceeds threshold."
      },
      {
        "scenario": "D: Network partition to Stripe for 2 minutes",
        "handling": "partial",
        "recommendation": "PREDICTION: First 5 requests each wait 10s timeout then fail. Under concurrent load, 5 failures accumulate in seconds, circuit opens. Circuit breaker then fails fast for 60s (good). At 60s, half-open test fires one request, waits 10s, fails (partition still active), circuit re-opens for 60s. Timeline: ~5-10s of thread starvation (5 threads × 10s timeout), then fast-fail for rest of 2 minutes. SURVIVABILITY: Service survives. Circuit breaker works as designed after initial thread drain. ~50s of degraded capacity at start, then clean fast-failures. FIX: Reduce Stripe timeout to 5s to drain initial failures faster. Consider idempotency keys for requests that timed out but may have succeeded at Stripe. The 10s timeout means 5 threads are blocked for 10s each during the initial detection window — with 20 threads, that's 25% capacity loss."
